Letters went home this week for all students in kindergarten that are not up to date on vaccines. If you received a letter for your child please get the required vaccines by 9/9/2020. After this date, the law provides that students NOT IN COMPLIANCE with these requirements MUST BE EXCLUDED from school until the student provides verification of the immunization received, has a scheduled plan signed by the physician, or obtains an exemption signed according to the provisions of the law. This also applies to any student doing blended learning. If you have any questions please call the school nurse at 740-493-2881.

Thanks!

--
Holly Tackett BSN, RN
Western Local Schools
District Nurse

Western Families and community businesses.

As you are fully aware, school is different this year in many areas. One area is recess. We have decided it's in the best interest of our students not to use the playground equipment. Because of this, students mainly walk during recess. We have started to purchase items (jump ropes, balls, etc) that each individual child or pair can use during recess. Several individuals and businesses have asked how they can help the school this year. Here is your chance.

We've created an Amazon wish list below with the needed items. The account is set for the items to ship to the school under Mrs. Bethany Whitt, Elementary Principal.

Thank you in advance for your continued support to Western students.

** If you share you'll need to copy and past the post. If not, just the link is shared.

post_text:
Hello Western Families! As we have started our first day of school, we have many changes. As we begin we would like to remind you of a few of those changes, regarding student drop off and pick up.
* Student drop off is in the back of the building from 7:45-8:00. A few procedure changes include: maintaining one lane of traffic at all times, not blocking any roadways, pull up to the on duty teacher, only students can exit the vehicle, the teacher will take your child's temperature.
* Student pick up in the back of the building begins at 2:45. Again, please maintain one lane of traffic at all times, do not block any roadways, students will be released to the parents, parents will need to remain in the vehicle, diminishing the congregation of large groups of people. If a parent/guardian must exit the vehicle, they must have a face covering unless they can maintain 6 feet of distance at all times.

We have to abide by guidelines in an attempt to keep our students and staff as safe as possible. Thank you for your understanding as we begin this different school year.

Back-to-school Bash....a little different this year.
Due to Covid we are unable to have our typical bash. However we are handing out backpacks with school supplies to Western students!

We ask families to stay in their cars, drive up to the bus entrance out front, give us your child’s grade and we will give you a backpack with their supplies.

**The supplies are for those who are coming to school, not remote learners. If your child chooses remote learning now but comes back to school within the year, we will have supplies for them if needed. Please share.￼
**The event is sponsored by Overflow Missions and local churches.

The following is a message from the school nurse:

As we make plans to return to school, please use this time to talk with your child/children about proper hand washing, covering cough/sneeze. Educating and encouraging your child to do these things will help stop the spread of germs and make the transition back to school easier.

If we don’t have enough to think about, please remember to keep up with your child’s vaccine schedule. Being immunized against vaccine preventable diseases is very important. Any student who is entering kindergarten, 7th and 12th grade are still required to get their vaccines to be able to attend school. Our Western SOMC site is scheduling appointments for vaccines. … More

We need a response ASAP. You can message the school through FB or call 740-493-2881. If no one answers, please leave a message.
Again, this is for EVERY current student in our district.

post_text: Ms J here. One way to fight boredom during quarantine, is to go on a scavenger hunt! There are several ways you can play. First, you can see how many of these items you can find in your neighborhood, take pictures and post them in the comments below. Secondly, you could go on the scavenger hunt on the internet! Use Google images to search for pictures of these items, then copy and paste them on a Google Doc. Finally, you could make a list of these items and check them off as you find them. The point is to take some time with family and have fun, no matter the type of technology you have access to! Enjoy!

post_text: Ms J here. A few weeks ago, I mentioned YouTube as a way to learn new skills. Today, I want to share how I've been using this social media service lately. I have been watching videos that show me how other people live. One of my new favorites is called "Special Books by Special Kids." A former special education teacher interviews people with special needs. A common theme shows up in all of his videos, that despite their different challenges, these people are just like you and me! They each have hopes and dreams, and all they really want is to be loved and accepted! Some of the deformities may be too shocking for little kids, but this is a good example of one all kids should see! … More

post_text:
Good afternoon Western families.

1. Governor DeWine just announced school will remain closed for the rest of the year. While this does not surprise us, we are so upset that we will not be able to finish out the year as we normally would.

2. I know you have a lot of questions as far as grades, if school will start early to make up for lost time, what about all the graduations? We will be meeting as an administration team to decide how to move forward. Once we have a plan in place, we will contact you.

3. It is very important that students make an effort on the packets that have been sent home. This will be our only way of getting grades for the last 9 weeks. All we ask is that an effort is made. If your students need extra help with completing the packets, please contact their teacher.

Families, if you need anything at all, please let us know.
Sending love and prayers to you all.

Mrs. Whitt & Mrs. Thompson

post_text:
Western Families

Thank you for your patience and understanding as we have tried to get student work to our students.

Unfortunately we are in a situation that no one asked for. We didn't ask for a virus to come causing the government to shut down school and we know you all didn't ask to be placed in the role of being a teacher. 🙂

We are required by the state to provide work to our students. We tried to make the work as simple as possible, with no new work, only review. All we ask is that students try their best to complete the work.

If you have any questions about the work, please contact your child's teacher. All of our grade levels have Facebook pages, and their email addresses were included in the packets. If you need another way to contact the teacher, please comment below and we will make sure they reach out to you.

Again, thank you for your patience and understanding. We appreciate our Western families!

text:
Western Families

Thank you for your patience and understanding as we have tried to get student work to our students.

Unfortunately we are in a situation that no one asked for. We didn't ask for a virus to come causing the government to shut down school and we know you all didn't ask to be placed in the role of being a teacher. 🙂

We are required by the state to provide work to our students. We tried to make the work as simple as possible, with no new work, only review. All we ask is that students try their best to complete the work.

If you have any questions about the work, please contact your child's teacher. All of our grade levels have Facebook pages, and their email addresses were included in the packets. If you need another way to contact the teacher, please comment below and we will make sure they reach out to you.

Again, thank you for your patience and understanding. We appreciate our Western families!

Mrs. Whitt & Mrs. Thompson

post_text: Hi there, Western Indians! Mrs. Dodds here! I hope you are all safe and well at home. I miss you so much!!! This is an earth friendly recycled paper mache project I started with some of my third graders. Even though we didn't get to paint it yet, they turned out awesome so far. We had so much fun I thought it would be great for any grade level! All you need is a plastic bottle, newspaper or paper towels, or really any thin scrap paper, tape, paint and paint brush. For the glue mixture you can use Elmer's glue mixed with water using a 3 to 1 ratio. 3 parts glue, one part water. If you don't have Elmer's glue I will post in the comments below alternative recipes. You DON'T have to make penguins! Use your imaginations! Please Post what you make online if you can! We'd love to see it! https://youtu.be/7S0CLBQpkzo

This message is for all students who are on the food service list. We will be having a hot meal for pick up tomorrow at the junior high gym/bus unloading area from 11 to 12. We will be providing enough food for two hot meals and for two breakfasts. We are not able to get any more power pack food until the middle of April so we’re going to have to do hot meals and breakfast. Our plan is to have food three days a week at this point. If you absolutely cannot pick it up or have someone pick it up for you please contact me at 740-493-3113 and we will try to figure out a plan to get it to you.

Ramen noodles packs
Macaroni and cheese boxes

Cans of ravioli

Canned vegetables

I woke up this morning with this on my mind. I was going to post it then but I just felt like I should wait to see what thoughts the rest of the day brought. I’m not very philosophical and I typically try to make jokes and lighten the mood whenever I can but I’m not sure this is really a time for either - at least not for me.

I know they are varied opinions about the coronavirus and the way it is being handled. That is very understandable and not atypical of any crisis or potential crisis. Everyone has an opinion, which is also completely normal. I can’t say I’m an expert on this in any way but there are a few things that I know. I would like to share a few of those thoughts about this… More

post_text: Do to the to the potential for black ice we will be having a two hour delay for February 27, 2020. Most of what I’m seeing on the road is standing water and hasn’t frozen but there is a potential for those places to freeze as it gets more toward daylight. There are some definite slick spots out there but I’m afraid they will get worse as it drops a few degrees before daylight so in the name of safety we’re going to have a two hour delay

post_text: If your child has been officially diagnosed as having the flu please be sure to call school and let us know. Our attendance rate is not terribly far off of normal but I’m kind of expecting this week to be rough. Hopefully I’m wrong. We brought in extra custodians on Friday night to disinfect both buildings and we have also disinfected all of the buses this week. This was in addition to our normal routine. Hoping this flu bug heads out soon but we are keeping an eye on our attendance rates and we will keep you updated. If your child is sick with flu-like symptoms please keep them home and take them to the doctor or bring them to the clinic at school. Thanks and have a great evening. ￼￼￼￼￼

post_text: The mission is a go!

post_text:
Help Miss Lori’s Preschool make a difference!

Miss Lori’s class is talking about how we can help others in our community, so we decided to take up donations for the local pound for the month of February. We would like to collect dog food, collars, leashes, toys, treats, blankets, balls, and cleaning supplies. We will also take up monetary donations to give to them to use for whatever their needs are. If you would like to help, please send in your donations and Miss Lori’s class will make sure it gets right to them.

Thank you for helping us teach our children the power of our caring community!

Miss Lori
